<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-cutting-the-rational-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    Cutting the Rational Numbers
  </title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Text before the first subdivision.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  
  <definition xml:id="definition-dedekind-cut">
    <title>
      Dedekind cut
    </title>
    
    <idx>
      dedekind cut
    </idx>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        A proper, non-empty subset <m> 0 \subseteq X \subseteq \Q </m> of the rational numbers <m> \Q </m> is called a <term> Dedekind cut </term> if it satisfies the following conditions:
      </p>
      
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            For all rational numbers <m> q_{ 1 } , q_{ 2 } \in \Q </m>, if <m> q_{ 1 } \leq q_{ 2 } </m> and <m> q_{ 2 } \in X </m>, then <m> q_{ 1 } \in X </m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        
        <li>
          <p>
            <m> X </m> does not have a maximum; that is, for all elements <m> q_{ 1 } \in X </m>, there is an element <m> q_{ 2 } \in X </m> so that <m> q_{ 1 } \lt q_{ 2 } </m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  
  <example xml:id="example-dedekind-cuts">
    <title>
      Dedekind cuts
    </title>
    
    <idx>
      rational Dedekind cut
    </idx>
    
    <notation>
      <usage>
        <m> X_{ q } </m>
      </usage>
      
      <description>
        <p>
          the rational Dedekind cut associated to <m> q </m>
        </p>
      </description>
    </notation>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each rational number <m> q \in \Q </m>, consider the subset
        
        <md>
          X_{ q } = \setmid{ p \in \Q }{ p \lt q }
        </md>
        
        of the rational numbers <m> \Q </m>. We observe that <m> X_{ q } </m> is a proper and non-empty subset of <m> \Q </m>, since it contains <m> q - 1 </m> but not <m> q </m> itself. Moreover, for all rational numbers <m> p_{ 1 } , p_{ 2 } \in \Q </m>, if <m> p_{ 1 } \leq p_{ 2 } </m> and <m> p_{ 2 } \in X_{ q } </m>, then
        
        <md>
          p_{ 1 } \leq p_{ 2 } \lt q
        </md>,
        
        and so <m> p_{ 1 } \in X_{ q } </m>. Finally, for all elements <m> p_{ 1 } \in X </m>, we observe that
        
        <md>
          p \lt p + \frac{ q - p }{ 2 } \lt p + \of{ q - p } = q
        </md>,
        
        so that <m> p + \frac{ q - p }{ 2 } \in X_{ q } </m>. In summary, we have shown that associated to each rational number <m> q \in \Q </m> is a Dedekind cut <m> X_{ q } </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  
  <p>
    We will see that the above construction realizes the rational numbers <m> \Q </m> as a subset of the set of Dedekind cuts. The Dedekind cuts which arise in this manner will be called <term> rational </term>. We will shortly see that not every Dedekind cut is rational.
  </p>
  
  <lemma xml:id="lemma-rational-dedekind-cuts">
    <title>
      Rational Dedekind cuts
    </title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        A Dedekind cut <m> X </m> is rational if and only if its complement <m> \Q \setminus X </m> has a minimum.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m> X </m> be a Dedekind cut, and suppose that <m> X = X_{ q } </m> for some rational number <m> q \in \Q </m>. Note that <m> X = X_{ q } </m> has complement
        
        <md>
          \Q \setminus X = \Q \setminus X_{ q } = \setmid{ p \in \Q }{ p \notin X_{ q } } = \setmid{ p \in \Q }{ p \geq q }
        </md>.
        
        This set contains <m> q </m>, since <m> q \geq q </m>. Moreover, <m> p \geq q </m> for all elements <m> p \in \Q \setminus X_{ q } </m>. Thus <m> \min \of{ \Q \setminus X } = q </m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Conversely, now suppose that <m> \Q \setminus X </m> has a minimum element, say <m> q = \min \of{ \Q \setminus X } \in \Q </m>. Let <m> p \in \Q </m>, and suppose that <m> p \geq q </m>. If <m> p \in X </m>, then that would imply that <m> q \in X </m>. This contradiction implies that <m> p \notin X </m>. On the other hand, if <m> p \lt q </m>, then <m> p \notin \Q \setminus X </m>, since <m> \min \of{ \Q \setminus X } = q </m>. Thus
        
        <md>
          X = \setmid{ p \in \Q }{ p \lt q } = X_{ q }
        </md>
        
        is rational.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </lemma>
  
  <proposition xml:id="proposition-not-all-dedekind-cuts-are-rational">
    <title>
      Irrational Dedekind cuts
    </title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        Not all Dedekind cuts are rational.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <proof>
      <p>
        Consider the subset
        
        <md>
          X = \setmid{ q \in \Q }{ q \lt 0 \textrm{ or } q^{ 2 } \lt 2 }
        </md>
        
        of the rational numbers <m> \Q </m>. We observe that <m> X </m> is a non-empty and proper subset of <m> \Q </m>, since it contains <m> 1 </m> but not <m> 2 </m>. Let <m> p_{ 1 } , p_{ 2 } \in \Q </m> be rational numbers, and suppose that <m> p_{ 1 } \leq p_{ 2 } </m> and <m> p_{ 2 } \in X </m>. If <m> p_{ 2 } \lt 0 </m>, then
        
        <md>
          p_{ 1 } \leq p_{ 2 } \lt 0
        </md>,
        
        and so <m> p_{ 1 } \in X </m>. On the other hand, if <m> p_{ 2 }^{ 2 } \lt 2 </m>, then either <m> p_{ 1 } \lt 0 </m> or <m> 0 \leq p_{ 1 } \leq p_{ 2 } </m>, in which case <m> p_{ 1 }^{ 2 } \leq p_{ 2 }^{ 2 } \lt 2 </m>. In either case, we conclude that <m> p_{ 1 } \in X </m>.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Finally, let <m> q \in X </m>. If <m> q \leq 0 </m>, then let <m> p = 1 </m>, and note that <m> p \in X </m> and <m> q \lt p </m>. On the other hand, suppose that <m> q \gt 0 </m> and <m> q^{ 2 } \lt 2 </m>, and consider the rational number
        
        <md>
          p = \frac{ 2 q + 2 }{ 2 + q } \in \Q
        </md>.
        
        Note that
        
        <md>
          p = \frac{ 2 q + 2 }{ 2 + q } = \frac{ 2 q + q^{ 2 } }{ 2 + q } + \frac{ 2 - q^{ 2 } }{ 2 + q } = q + \frac{ 2 - q^{ 2 } }{ 2 + q } \gt q
        </md>,
        
        and
        
        <md>
          <mrow>
            2 - p^{ 2 } \amp = \frac{ 2 \of{ 2 + q }^{ 2 } }{ \of{ 2 + q }^{ 2 } } - \frac{ \of{ 2 q + 2 }^{ 2 } }{ \of{ 2 + q }^{ 2 } }
          </mrow>
          
          <mrow>
            \amp = \frac{ 4 - 2 q^{ 2 } }{ \of{ 2 + q }^{ 2 } } = \frac{ 2 \of{ 2 - q^{ 2 } } }{ \of{ 2 + q }^{ 2 } } \gt 0
          </mrow>
        </md>,
        
        so that <m> p^{ 2 } \lt 2 </m>; that is, <m> p \in X </m>. We conclude that <m> X </m> is a Dedekind cut.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        We note that <m> X </m> has complement
        
        <md>
          \Q \setminus X = \setmid{ q \in \Q }{ q \geq 0 \textrm{ and } q^{ 2 } \geq 2 }
        </md>.
        
        In fact, since <m> q^{ 2 } \neq 2 </m> for all rational numbers <m> q \in \Q </m>,
        
        <md>
          \Q \setminus X = \setmid{ q \in \Q }{ q \geq 0 \textrm{ and } q^{ 2 } \gt 2 }
        </md>.
        
        This set has no minimum element, and so <m> X </m> is not rational.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      Text after the last subdivision.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</subsection>

